Description: The iconic duck, a male MALLARD has a green head, yellow bill, and some regular-looking feathers on the rest of its body. It's charismatic, adaptable, and found worldwide.
The OSTRICH is really too big to be a bird, but it has feathers and lays eggs, so there you have it. They're fast, bad-tempered, and as dumb as they look.
A powerful symbol of both freedom and bellicosity, the EAGLE is a formidable predator, with some species hunting prey up to 8 times their own body weight.
The SWAN is known for its beauty and grace, but also they're basically just surly geese who did a semester abroad in France and now think they're better than other comparably large waterfowl.
Despite its beak and egg-laying the PLATYPUS is not a bird, but a marsupial. It can't fly and doesn't have feathers.
While not yet the state bird of Florida, the FLAMINGO, with its pink plumage and easygoing littoral lifestyle, is a symbol of just letting the vibes be, man.
Curelest of the shorebirds, the SEAGULL is known for being loud and rowdy and stealing things from little kids who were just having a nice day on the beach.
